<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1436,1470,2035]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,1578,1603]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The dorsal habitus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[715,841,1579,1603]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpinus">
<emphasis box="[715,841,1579,1603]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">E. vulpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[856,951,1578,1602]" captionStart="FIGURE 101" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[183,1405,430,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-101@65.[166,1420,415,1927]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 101. Epimetopus vulpinus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
) is very similar to that of other members of the 
<emphasis box="[192,315,1614,1638]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Plaumanni</emphasis>
group. It differs from the others in having slightly more ovate elytra, and usually a larger V-shaped fascia on the elytra. It is the smallest member of the group (ca. 
<quantity box="[867,971,1650,1674]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.17" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="2.17">2.17 mm</quantity>
). Males have the clypeus upturned, as do 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Oliva" authorityYear="1986" box="[151,254,1687,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vianai">
<emphasis box="[151,254,1687,1710]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">E. vianai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[311,473,1686,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multiportus">
<emphasis box="[311,473,1686,1710]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">E. multiportus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Examination of the male genitalia will be essential for reliable determinations. The aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[272,371,1722,1746]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–106" captionStartId="67.[151,264,1780,1803]" captionTargetBox="[225,1365,240,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-110@67.[205,1381,223,1735]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 103–106. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
) is much broader (in both views) than others in the species group; the dorsal processes are shaped differently and are broader basally than those of other species; and the median lobe above the bases of the dorsal processes is not parallel-sided.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="65" lastPageNumber="66" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1436,1470,2035]" lastBlockId="65.[151,1436,151,356]" lastPageId="65" lastPageNumber="66" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis box="[199,344,1830,1855]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1830,1855]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Description</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Size: 
<typeStatus box="[421,519,1830,1854]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length from anterior margin of pronotum to elytral apices) 2.17/1.19; head (width) 0.59; pronotum 0.81/0.87; elytra 1.44/1.19. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[1258,1356,1866,1890]" captionStart="FIGURE 101" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[183,1405,430,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-101@65.[166,1420,415,1927]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 101. Epimetopus vulpinus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
). Head piceous, maxillary palpi light brown; pronotum dark brown to piceous; elytra dark brown except yellowish on carinae in basal ¼, large V-shaped fascia near midlength, and at apical ¼ of elytra; venter piceous; legs rufous. Pronotum with hood carinae very slightly arcuate, almost straight, converging and confluent anteriorly, grooved throughout; secondary lateral very small, almost absent. Elytron with four strong granulate carinae, third interrupted anteriorly for distance of ca. 3 punctures; punctures round or oval, large, each with small granule at anterior margin, non-carinate intervals without granules. Protibiae slightly emarginate on inner margin, almost straight. Metaventral depression moderately deep and wide, ca. nine granules along base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1436,151,356]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,260,284]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in reference to the dorsal processes of the median lobe of the aedeagus, which are shaped like fox ears.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
